{
  "text": "Proanthocyanidins are found in many common foodstuffs and they have a long history in human diet [CITATION_1] . Flavan-3-ols and especially epigallocatechin gallate are common in green tea and green tea preparations. Green tea flavan-3-ols have been implicated to have both beneficial and harmful effects on human health [CITATION_2] . Few toxicological studies have been made with the purified individual flavan-3-ols. Studies have demonstrated the lack of mutagenic activity of several flavan-3-ols in bacterial reverse mutation tests [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Epigallocatechin was shown to exhibit weak mutagenic activity [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . Several pure procyanidins including dimers, a trimer and a polymer fraction were shown to be non-mutagenic in the Ames test [CITATION_9] .",
  "correct_citation": {
